<subsection xml:id="subsec-Reciprocal-of-fractions">
        <title>Reciprocal of fractions</title>
        <activity>
           <p><alert>Work in groups</alert></p>
           <p>
                1. Form groups of at least two learners.
           </p>
           <p>
                2. The first learner selects any number between 1 and 20.
           </p>
           <p>
                3. The second learner selects any number between 2 and 20.
           </p>
           <p>
                4. Write a fraction using the first learner's number as the numerator and the second learner's number as the denominator.
           </p>
           <p>
                5. Now, write another fraction by swapping the positions, use the second learner's number as the numerator and the first learner's number as the denominator.
           </p>
           <p>
                6. Multiply the two fractions and observe the result.
           </p>
           <p>
                7. Discuss with your classmates what you notice about the two fractions and their product.
           </p>
        </activity>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        To find the reciprocal of a fraction, swap the numerator and the denominator.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The product of a fraction and its reciprocal is <m>1.</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What is the reciprocal of <m>\frac{11}{23}</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    To get the reciprocal of <m>\frac{11}{23}</m>, we swap the numerator and the denominator.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{11}{23} \text{ to get } \frac{23}{11}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The the reciprocal of <m>\frac{11}{23} \text{ is } \frac{23}{11}.</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What is the reciprocal of <m>6 \frac{4}{5}</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Convert <m>6 \frac{4}{5}</m> into an improper fraction.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>6 \frac{4}{5} = \frac{(5 \times 6)+4}{3 \times 7} = \frac{34}{5}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Swap the numerator and the denominator.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\frac{34}{5} \text{ to get } \frac{5}{34}</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The reciprocal of <m>6 \frac{4}{5} \text{ is } \frac{5}{34}.</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
